2","1509":"1509","about 1520":"about 1520","2 March 1525":"2 March 1525","Rougham, Suffolk, England":"Rougham, Suffolk, England","Rougham,, Suffolk, England":"Rougham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Rougham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Rougham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goldingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Goldingham Hall in Bulmer, or Goldingham Farm in Braintree (Essex)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Goldingham was born in 1509, in Rougham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Goldingham Esq and Thomasine de Liston. She married John Drury about 1521, in Roug